1. React as a Single Page Application (SPA)

React is mainly used to build Single Page Applications (SPA).

In an SPA:
The browser loads only one HTML page (index.html).
Page content changes without reloading the whole page.
This gives faster performance and a smooth user experience.
React updates only the required parts of the page instead of loading new pages every time.

2. Virtual DOM in React

React uses a Virtual DOM, which is a lightweight copy of the real DOM.
When we modify a component, React:
Updates the Virtual DOM
Compares it with the previous version (Diffing)
Updates only the changed parts in the real DOM

Advantages
Faster updates
Better performance
Efficient rendering

3. Components in React

React applications are made of components
Each file we create in React is a component
Components are reusable, independent, and easy to maintain

Example:

Header component
Footer component
Home component

4. Page Navigation: JavaScript vs React

Page Navigation in JavaScript
Uses window.location or links
Full page reload happens
Slower performance
Page Navigation in React
Uses React Router
No page reload
Only components change
Faster and smoother navigation

5. Creating a React Project using Vite

Command
npm create vite@latest project_name

Explanation
npm → Node Package Manager (used to run commands)
create → Keyword to create a project
vite → Build tool for fast development
@latest → Optional, installs latest version
project_name → Name of the project

6. Running a React Project
Command
npm run dev
run → Keyword
dev → Development server in Vite

7. React Folder Structure

Important Files and Folders

node_modules
Contains pre-built libraries and packages

public
Used for static files like images and icons

index.html
Core file
React app runs inside this file
Modified only for SEO optimization

package.json
Meta information of the project
Project name, scripts, dependencies

package-lock.json
Exact dependency versions

vite.config.js
Vite configuration file

eslint.config.js
Code quality and linting rules

.gitignore
Files ignored by Git

8. JSX (JavaScript XML)
JSX allows writing HTML-like code inside JavaScript
Makes UI code easier to understand
File extension: .jsx

Example:

<h1>Hello React</h1>

9. File Connection Flow in React
index.html → main.jsx → App.jsx → Components
Explanation
index.html connects to main.jsx
main.jsx renders App.jsx
App.jsx acts as the entry point
Other components are rendered inside App.jsx

StrictMode
Used during development
Helps detect errors and repetitive tasks
Does not affect production build

10. Component File Structure (JSX)
General structure of a React component:
// import files/packages
import React from 'react';
// function
function Home() {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Home Page</h1>
        </div>
    );
}

// export
export default Home;

11. Types of Components in React
1. Functional Components (Most Common)
Written using functions
Simple and easy to use
Uses Hooks
Boilerplate shortcut: rfc

2. Class Components

Written using ES6 classes
Uses lifecycle methods
More complex
Boilerplate shortcut: rcc

Differences
Functional Component	Class Component
Uses functions	Uses classes
Uses Hooks	Uses lifecycle methods
Simple and fast	More complex

Most commonly used	Less commonly used
12. Path Shortcuts
./ → Exit from a file
../ → Exit from a folder

13. Import and Export Rule
Do not mention file extensions while importing
Example:
import Home from "./Home";
✔ Correct

import Home from "./Home.jsx";
❌ Incorrect


